      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Understanding Your Buyer Pool When Selling in Brisbane: Owner-Occupiers vs Investors
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The type of buyer most likely to purchase your property determines how you should present it, how you should price it, and which method of sale will produce the best result.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the most useful questions to answer before listing a Brisbane property is: who is actually going to buy this? The answer matters more than most sellers realise. The type of buyer most likely to purchase your property determines how you should present it, which method of sale gives you the best chance of a strong result, and where you should direct your pre-sale preparation budget. A selling strategy built around the wrong buyer type is a common and costly mistake.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The two primary buyer types for residential property</h2>
      <p>For residential property in Brisbane, the two primary buyer types are owner-occupiers and investors. Owner-occupiers are buying to live in the property. Investors are buying to rent it out and generate a return on capital. Each group approaches the purchase differently, values different things, and responds to different selling strategies.</p>

      <p>There is also a third category that sits between the two: the buyer who intends to live in the property now but holds it as a long-term investment, or the buyer who wants to add value through renovation before selling or renting. This buyer type shares some characteristics of both groups. For the purposes of structuring a sale campaign, however, it is useful to understand which end of the spectrum your likely buyer pool sits closest to.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What owner-occupiers care about</h2>
      <p>Owner-occupiers are buying a place to live, and their decision is part financial and part emotional. They care about liveability: the layout of the home, how natural light moves through the rooms, storage, the kitchen and bathroom standard, and how the property functions as a daily living environment. They care about proximity to good schools, walkability, neighbourhood character, and the feel of the street.</p>

      <p>Presentation matters significantly for this buyer type. A home that has been properly styled, decluttered, and photographed to show its best features will appeal more strongly to owner-occupiers than the same property presented as-is. The emotional connection that drives a buyer to stretch their budget at auction or make a strong private treaty offer is built through presentation. An owner-occupier buying a family home in Morningside is not running a spreadsheet; they are imagining their life in the property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What investors care about</h2>
      <p>Investors are buying a financial asset. The questions they ask are about yield, vacancy risk, and tenant quality. Yield is the relationship between the purchase price and the achievable weekly rent, expressed as an annual percentage of the purchase price. An investor buying at $900,000 who can achieve $700 per week in rent has a gross yield of approximately 4.0%. That number drives their assessment of whether the property is worth the price.</p>

      <p>Investors also care about tenant quality, practical rental appeal, and body corporate rules if the property is in a complex. A unit that is in a well-managed building with low body corporate fees, strong rental demand, and few restrictions on tenants is a more attractive investment than one in a building with high fees, special levies, or restrictions that reduce the tenant pool. Heavy styling and premium finishes that impress owner-occupier buyers have less impact on investor buyers, who are looking at the numbers first.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How property type determines the buyer pool</h2>
      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, the buyer pool is heavily determined by property type. Houses in well-regarded suburbs attract a buyer pool that is predominantly owner-occupiers: families looking to upsize, couples buying their first home, and owner-occupiers looking to downsize without leaving a suburb they have lived in for decades. These buyers are competing for a limited stock of houses in suburbs with strong school catchments and established neighbourhood character, and their competition with each other is what drives strong auction results.</p>

      <p>Units and apartments attract a more mixed buyer pool. Smaller units, particularly in high-density buildings, attract a higher proportion of investors because the yield profile suits investment purposes better than family-sized living. Larger units and townhouses in boutique developments attract more owner-occupiers, particularly younger buyers and downsizers who want to reduce maintenance without leaving the suburb. Properties near universities and the CBD attract a higher proportion of student rental investors.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the buyer pool affects method of sale</h2>
      <p>Auction works best when you have a buyer pool of motivated owner-occupiers who are competing emotionally for a property they want to live in. The dynamics of a public auction, where buyers can see each other competing and the event creates urgency, draws on the emotional engagement of the owner-occupier buyer in a way that consistently drives prices above what a more measured private treaty process achieves.</p>

      <p>An investor-dominated buyer pool responds less predictably to auction. Investors are running yield calculations, and they have a clear walk-away point determined by the numbers rather than emotional attachment. When the bidding exceeds the price at which the yield makes sense, most investors stop bidding. This can result in auctions that pass in at figures that would have been cleared comfortably if the property had been offered to an owner-occupier buyer pool through a well-run private treaty campaign with time for buyers to conduct due diligence and secure finance.</p>

      <p>For properties with a mixed buyer pool, the right method of sale requires genuine judgement from an agent who knows the local market well. The composition of the active buyer pool at the time of listing, not just the property type in the abstract, should inform the recommendation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the buyer pool should shape your preparation</h2>
      <p>If your property is likely to attract primarily owner-occupiers, the case for investing in quality styling and professional photography is strong. The return on well-executed presentation in a property targeting owner-occupiers is consistently positive: the gap between a well-styled campaign and an unstyled one regularly exceeds the cost of the styling by a multiple of two to five in Brisbane's inner east.</p>

      <p>If your property is likely to attract primarily investors, the priorities shift. Clean, freshly painted, well-maintained, and professionally photographed matters. But a $6,000 styling spend delivering a magazine-quality presentation to a buyer who is comparing your property's yield against three other investment options is not the highest-return use of your preparation budget. Your agent should be direct with you about this trade-off rather than recommending maximum spend regardless of the buyer profile.</p>

      <p>For properties in Brisbane's inner east that are houses in good school catchments, the default assumption should be an owner-occupier buyer pool and the preparation strategy should reflect that. The streets around Morningside State School, Bulimba State School, and Camp Hill State School consistently attract owner-occupiers with the financial capacity to compete strongly at auction, and presentation quality has a direct and measurable effect on the outcome.</p>

